Principal ballerina for the New York City Ballet @tilerpeck was told in 2019 that a herniated disc in her neck could prematurely end her dance career. Naturally she felt hopeless and scared.

Tiler joins me from her dressing room on this week’s episode of Beyond the Prescription to talk about her epic recovery. After listening to her own body, she embarked on a journey of self-discovery. The combination of rest, boundary-setting, and holistic healthcare helped the dancer return to the stage stronger than ever. 

This one was particularly special for me, as Tiler embodies the concept of health as a process, not an outcome. Hear the full episode when it drops tomorrow, or you can get early access by subscribing to my newsletter at https://lucymcbride.substack.com/welcome.

First up for our 2022 Standouts is Gian Carlo Perez of The Washington Ballet! ✨

“Gian Carlo Perez captivated audience members last February as Prince Siegfried in The Washington Ballet’s production of Swan Lake. Siegfried can often feel like a flat character—especially when he’s unable to discern the difference between Odile and Odette. However, Perez’s spunk and acting skills took this age-old role to greater depths and complexities.
Unafraid to act with his whole body, his facial expressions gave audience members a sense of the vast emotions Siegfried is experiencing on his journey from love to betrayal and, ultimately, despair. Perez’s Cuban training was also on full display, with skyscraping jumps and consistently smooth turns. He walked the finest line of basking in the glory of his solos, while playing the ever-doting prince and partner to his Odette/Odile, Eun Won Lee. With seven seasons under his belt at The Washington Ballet, Perez has established himself as a premier artist, a dancer who demonstrates both versatility and emotional proclivity. —Katherine Beard”

📸: @giancarlo_perez_dancer er; photo by @xmbphotography, courtesy @thewashingtonballet 
📝: @classylassy101

#Repost from @marylandyouthballet celebrating my amazing mother! Not only was she the beloved first ballet teacher to generations of young dancers, she was also the founder of #MusicandMotion leading the way in IDEA by creating a dance program for children with mobility limitations 
🙏🏻💫
・・・
For over 50 years, we have had countless accomplished women in our MYB community and for #WomensHistoryMonth, we are proud to highlight Jennifer Cox, a retired faculty member and the co-founder of MYB's unique Music & Motion program for children with physical disabilities. "Jenny" together with Dr. Rebecca Leonard (@eiapt), a pediatric physical therapist, established a special assisted dance class to introduce young children with disabilities to the joy of dance movement. This was the natural outgrowth of her over 30 years of teaching ballet to young children. Cox, originally from New Zealand, was a soloist with Ballet Petite in Christ Church and is mother to Julie Kent, acclaimed principal ballerina with American Ballet Theatre, Artistic Director of The Washington Ballet, and soon to be Co-Artistic Director of the Houston Ballet. "Seeing that we came from a ballet family, I wanted to make sure that my granddaughter, who was born with cerebral palsy, had the opportunity to be able to feel the movement of dance," says Cox. 

In 2006, the program received a $25,000 grant to develop a one-of-a-kind system of harnesses which were installed in one of the studios in MYB's home in Downtown Silver Spring. Leonard says, “We always thought it would be great fun for those children who need a device, be it a walker or canes, to be able to get into a body-suspension weight-bearing system. The spring-equipped harnesses, suspended from the ceiling, opened up possibilities for moving about in the space—turns, backwards stepping and sideward stepping, even spinning motion. For many students, orthotics come off when the harnesses go on. Therapeutically, it has given them great opportunities. and we’ve tried to bring that together with teaching ballet.” 

#MarylandYouthBallet #WomensHistoryMonth2023 #MusicAndMotion

📣 Julie Kent (@juliekentofficial), Artistic Director of @thewashingtonballet, has been announced as the Spring 2023 Commencement Speaker for @americanuniversity's College of Arts and Sciences. Ms. Kent became the Artistic Director of The Washington Ballet in July 2016. As the longest-serving ballerina in American Ballet Theatre’s 83-year history and the mother of two children, she has helped redefine the image of the American Ballerina. In July 2023, Kent will assume the role of Co-Artistic Director of @houstonballet, leading alongside Stanton Welch, AM.

"Having Julie Kent as the commencement speaker for the College this year was important to me. As my first AU commencement as Dean of the College, I wanted a speaker who is a touchstone for both AU and DC. Julie has been a partner with AU for years, and she is a role model for our students in all of the arts, especially in dance. She has strong and historical connections to the local DC dance and arts communities, and this commencement event marks a goodbye for her before she leaves for a new career and life in Houston," remarked CAS Dean Linda Aldoory (@laldoory).
